The field of IEMS is still developing, therefore many aspects of these systems need to be improved. Regarding indirect control systems, explainability of recommendations remains an issue that needs further study. The lack of explainable recommendations lead users to ignore advice, reducing the effectiveness of a system and the trustworthiness of it (Zhang etÂ al. 2020). Each recommendation should be accompanied by answers to the questions âwhy to perform an actionâ and âwhat the benefits areâ (Himeur etÂ al. 2021). In (EM)3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^3$$\end{document} system, (Sardianos etÂ al. 2020a; Varlamis etÂ al. 2022b), each recommendation had a reasoning and a persuasion feature, which resulted in 20% increase in the acceptance ratio. Moreover, Wilkinson etÂ al. (2021) presented that it is more effective to provide justifications on why an action should be performed rather than why not.
